As the Sydney Summer abruptly ended, with a deluge of rain,one of the plus sides, is the annual release of an Autumn Seasonal from @doctorsordersbrewing.  This year, Doc has canned â€˜Electrolyte Serumâ€™ a rhubarb infused gose, that was originally brewed for the 2nd birthday of The Alehouse. Reproduced for SCBW opening Gala Party Oct 2014.  The gose style was a practically extinct style of top fermented Gose beer that originated in Goslar, Germany, but started to re-emerge in the 80â€™s.  Then Doctors Orders were the first to commercially introduce the style to Australia in 2010.  Since then Doc has brewed several versions, resulting in Electrolyte Serum becoming their 2nd canned release.  Upon opening the nose has a dominant lemon characteristic with some coriander.  On taste the immediate tartness is well balanced with the saltiness that dries the palate on finish.  The rhubarb compliments not just to the sharpness, but a subtle sweetness that adds to the balance of the beer.  At 4% ABV, and while the Sun may not be out at the moment, a 4pk of these, sunshine or not, would go down well regardless of the weather.

An established Australian barbecue restaurant, this place serves up consistently tasty food at affordable prices.  Long queues form here daily, and advance reservations are highly recommended, to avoid waiting up to 1 hour or more.  While it looks visually similar, each cut of meat tastes distinct, owing to the different barbecue basting sauces used. Utterly delicious and satisfiying. Must try. . . . Hurricane's Grill Shop 433 Level 2, Harbourside Shopping Centre Darling Drive Sydney New South Wales 2000 Australia

Chris is reading Mr A his story tonight. And I'm figuring out where to hang my new KD I found today!  This framed poster is huge, and in perfect condition and dwarfed 5ft me when I had to carry it to my car.  Contrary to IG posts, I'm not always 'on the hunt' for Ken Done pieces! But lots of people have been asking me where I find all this Ken Done - and honestly it's a combo of luck, education and #locationlocation.  I'm really open to travelling to different areas in Melbourne, and I find that the older demographic areas usually have a higher concentration of KD. Similarly I personally have a (weird) visual memory and usually I can quickly scan and recognise a print quite quickly (usually from searching ebay, etsy, gumtree, artbooks etc)  While clothes are probably the most difficult to find, Linen, Kitchen Linens, scarves and bags are normally the best place to start. Today I am another year older and it's days like today that introspection comes easiest. Lately as a part of my endeavours to build a little side hustle, I've started to follow some really cool people on social media. Each are passionate about the environment and  are concerned about the amount of waste that we as humans produce. In a climate where it often feels like you're among the minority, where the battle is all up hill, where people often turn a blind eye, it is heartening to know that these people exist and are doing every little bit they can to make change happen. This is what drives me. My greatest hope is that I can inspire others to re-imagine how they are doing things, to make small (or big) changes and to educate themselves and their families.  So, here's a tip for you: carry your own re-usable cup! Ask your favourite barista to make your coffee in your cup, not a disposable. You don't give up coffee - nobody wants a mass of caffeine deprived tyrants roaming the streets...but this small change will help to reduce the 1 billion odd coffee cups (most of which contain plastic)  making it into landfill in Australian each year. #travelmug #reusablecup #environmentallyfriendly #reducereuserecycle #stopthewaste #reducelandfill #mothernature #ifnotforyouthenwho #doitforaustralia #doitfortheearth #sydneycity #sydney #australia #norwex

APRIL 11, 2017 2:08 A.M EST, 7:08 AM #London, and 4:08 PM in #Sydney. The #PinkMoon, also known as April's #FullMoon. Although we won't literally see the color #pink when we gaze above tonight, April's full moon is called the pink moon because it was how our #indigenous peoples here in the U.S. kept time and track of changes in #nature: with this moon, it was the arrival of #mosspink, one of the first #springtime flowers, signifying #change. "As above, so below." Below is a picture I took last year at #Keukenhof, the #GardenOfEurope in Lisse, the #Netherlands. There is only a short period of time each year to experience Keukenhof, and it is so #beautiful! A truly stunning array of flowers in all different shades of color...it is a must for your #bucketlist!  Now, from an #astrological standpoint, the Pink Moon will be in 22 degrees #Libra. Wherever Libra falls in your natal chart, you can expect issues related to the theme of that particular astrological house...and these may be the issues that have finally reached their culmination, so the Universe may request or even demand #change from you.  For your #meditation of the full #moon, think of what changes are needed in your #life, and if you have your natal chart and can see where 22 degrees Libra falls in it, all the better.  But look to #nature for #inspiration on where these changes are leading you, just as the Native Americans did before dreadful "time management" became a buzzword in today's world.
